plan_id: architecture-extensibility-review-20260421
title: "Architecture & Extensibility Review — Backlog for Future Planning"
status: draft
created: "2026-04-21"
origin: "Fresh full-codebase review, architecture and extensibility focus"

notes: |
  This is a holding plan for identified architectural gaps and extensibility
  improvements. Items have NOT been sequenced or scoped — they are raw findings
  for the owner to triage, group, and schedule into execution waves.
  Severity is architectural impact, not implementation effort.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FINDING AREAS
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

areas:
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # A: Dual-Lane Maintenance Burden (src/ vs fsrc/)
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: A01
    area: dual-lane
    severity: critical
    status: resolved
    resolved_at: "2026-04-22"
    resolution: >
      fsrc/src/prism/ promoted to canonical src/prism/. Old src/ lane deleted.
      Single unified codebase with plugin-registry-driven DI. See PRD v6.0.0.
    title: "Two codebases in one repo — src/ and fsrc/ must converge"
    detail: |
      RESOLVED 2026-04-22: fsrc->src migration complete. Single src/prism/ lane.
      Original finding: src/prism/ and fsrc/src/prism/ were parallel implementations of the same
      app. The fsrc lane has better architecture (pure scanner_core, plugin
      registry, registry-driven DI) but src/ was the production surface
      (api.py, cli.py, scanner.py at 827 lines).

      This dual-lane situation means:
        - Every bug fix must land twice.
        - Tests run twice, diverge silently.
        - Developers don't know which lane to read for canonical behaviour.

      What needs to happen:
        - Promote fsrc/ to be the single source of truth.
        - Port any src/-only behaviour that is genuinely production-necessary.
        - Delete src/ once parity is confirmed.
        - Update CI, imports, docs, demos to point at the unified lane.

    blockers:
      - "scan_kernel/orchestrator.py in src/ has no fsrc equivalent yet"
      - "api.py/cli.py in src/ import from scanner.py which has no fsrc equivalent"
      - "Some scanner_compat, scanner_extensions, scanner_analysis surface has no fsrc mapping"

  - id: A02
    area: dual-lane
    severity: high
    title: "scanner.py (827 lines) in src/ is still the live runtime path"
    detail: |
      Despite multiple godfile-decomposition waves, src/prism/scanner.py still
      stands at 827 lines and is the entry point for api.py and cli.py. fsrc
      has no equivalent runtime entry. Until fsrc takes over, scanner.py cannot
      be retired and all new features require two implementations.

    what_to_do:
      - Map all public entry points called from api.py and cli.py into scanner.py
      - Build equivalent fsrc entry paths through scanner_kernel/orchestrator
      - Flip api.py and cli.py to fsrc paths behind a feature flag or lane switch
      - Retire scanner.py

  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # B: Plugin System Gaps
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: B01
    area: plugin-system
    severity: high
    title: "No dynamic plugin discovery — everything is hardcoded at bootstrap"
    detail: |
      Plugins (Ansible, Kubernetes, Terraform) are registered in defaults.py and
      the registry bootstrap. There is no mechanism to discover plugins from
      installed packages (e.g., setuptools entry_points), from a plugin directory
      on disk, or from user-supplied config.

      This means adding a new platform requires:
        - Implementing the plugin classes
        - Modifying defaults.py or bootstrap code
        - Shipping a new Prism release

      For a tool intended to be extensible across platforms, this is too rigid.

    what_to_do:
      - Add entry_points-based plugin discovery (group: prism.scanner_plugins)
      - Allow a plugin_dirs config key to load plugins from filesystem paths
      - Registry.discover() method that runs at bootstrap and collects plugins
      - Ensure deferred loading is preserved for startup performance

  - id: B02
    area: plugin-system
    severity: high
    title: "No plugin versioning or compatibility contract enforcement"
    detail: |
      Plugins implement interfaces (VariableDiscoveryPlugin, FeatureDetectionPlugin, etc.)
      but there is no version declaration on either side. If prism changes an
      interface, old plugins silently break at runtime.

      Shape validation exists in defaults.py (_validate_plugin_shape) but it
      is only called for fallback/default paths — not for all registered plugins.

    what_to_do:
      - Add PRISM_PLUGIN_API_VERSION to interface classes
      - Registry validates version compatibility on registration
      - Emit a clear error (not a shape-validation warning) on API mismatch
      - Document the plugin API contract in docs/

  - id: B03
    area: plugin-system
    severity: medium
    title: "Plugin isolation is zero — all plugins share the same process"
    detail: |
      Third-party plugins run in the same Python process as Prism core. A
      misbehaving plugin can corrupt process state, leak memory, or crash the
      entire scan. For a tool meant to scan arbitrary Ansible repos with
      arbitrary plugins, this is a real risk.

    what_to_do:
      - Evaluate subprocess isolation for untrusted/third-party plugins
      - At minimum: document the trust model clearly ("plugins are trusted code")
      - Consider a lightweight plugin sandbox protocol (stdin/stdout JSON RPC)

  - id: B04
    area: plugin-system
    severity: medium
    title: "Singleton plugin instances in defaults.py are a hidden global state risk"
    detail: |
      defaults.py holds module-level singleton fallback plugin instances:
        _TASK_LINE_PARSING_FALLBACK = DefaultTaskLineParsingPolicyPlugin()
        _YAML_PARSING_FALLBACK = YAMLParsingPolicyPlugin()
        ...
      These are intentionally stateless (comment says so), but there is no
      enforcement. If any plugin class acquires mutable state in the future,
      this becomes a cross-caller contamination bug.

    what_to_do:
      - Add a stateless marker (e.g., PLUGIN_IS_STATELESS = True) to plugin classes
      - Registry validates the marker on registration for singleton-eligible plugins
      - Alternatively, always use factory functions for fallback plugins

  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # C: Core Orchestration Gaps
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: C01
    area: core-orchestration
    severity: high
    title: "No scan phase event system — cross-cutting concerns can't hook in"
    detail: |
      The scan pipeline (extract → discover → detect → render) is a hard-coded
      sequential call chain. There is no mechanism for plugins or external code
      to observe or intercept scan phases.

      This makes it impossible to add:
        - Progress reporting without modifying core
        - Custom validation steps
        - Metrics/tracing instrumentation
        - Caching layers

    what_to_do:
      - Define a ScanPhaseEvent protocol (phase_name, context, metadata)
      - DIContainer or ScannerContext accepts optional event_listeners: list[Callable]
      - Core emits events at phase boundaries (pre/post extract, discover, render, etc.)
      - First consumer: a progress reporter for CLI streaming output

  - id: C02
    area: core-orchestration
    severity: high
    title: "All I/O is synchronous — large repos will block"
    detail: |
      Every file read (YAML, task files, templates, README) is synchronous.
      For a role with hundreds of task files, scanning is single-threaded I/O.
      No async, no parallel file loading, no worker pools.

    what_to_do:
      - Benchmark current performance on a large role (100+ task files)
      - Evaluate asyncio adoption vs. ThreadPoolExecutor for file I/O
      - Candidate hot path: load_yaml_file calls in scanner_extract
      - Ensure plugin interface remains sync-compatible (async plugins optional)

  - id: C03
    area: core-orchestration
    severity: medium
    title: "No scan result caching — identical inputs are re-scanned every time"
    detail: |
      Each scan call re-reads all files from disk and re-processes from scratch.
      For prism-learn workflows that scan the same role repeatedly (e.g., refresh
      batches), this is pure waste.

    what_to_do:
      - Define a cache key: hash of role_path contents + scan_options
      - Optional scan cache backend (in-memory LRU, filesystem, Redis)
      - DIContainer wires cache backend as an optional plugin seam
      - Cache is opt-in via scan_options["cache_backend"]

  - id: C04
    area: core-orchestration
    severity: medium
    title: "DIContainer is hand-rolled and grows a new factory per new plugin type"
    detail: |
      Every time a new plugin extension point is added, DIContainer gets:
        - A new factory_X method
        - A new inject_mock_X method
        - A new _mocks["X"] check in the factory

      This is the right pattern for explicit wiring, but it doesn't scale. The
      class is already 360+ lines for ~12 plugin slots.

    what_to_do:
      - Consider a generic slot registration: di.register_factory("slot_name", fn)
      - Keep typed convenience methods as thin wrappers over the generic mechanism
      - Or: accept the growth and enforce a 500-line size budget with a CI check

  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # D: Configuration
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: D01
    area: configuration
    severity: medium
    title: "Configuration constants are scattered — no single config schema"
    detail: |
      Config lives in:
        - scanner_config/ (section, patterns, etc.)
        - scanner_plugins/defaults.py (fallback singleton instances)
        - scan_request.py (build_run_scan_options_canonical defaults)
        - scanner_core/scanner_context.py (_REQUIRED_SCAN_OPTION_KEYS)
        - Hardcoded strings throughout (e.g., "ansible", "prism")

      There is no single schema for what a valid scan_options dict looks like,
      no config validation at entry, and no structured defaults layer.

    what_to_do:
      - Define a ScanOptionsSchema (pydantic or TypedDict with explicit defaults)
      - All entry points (api.py, cli.py) validate/coerce inputs against schema
      - Move _REQUIRED_SCAN_OPTION_KEYS into the schema definition
      - Document every key with type, default, and description

  - id: D02
    area: configuration
    severity: low
    title: "No environment variable support for config keys"
    detail: |
      Users can only configure Prism via CLI flags, YAML config files, and
      API call arguments. There is no PRISM_* environment variable support.
      This makes it hard to configure in containerised/CI environments.

    what_to_do:
      - Define a PRISM_* env var namespace for common options
      - Env vars are lower priority than explicit API/CLI options
      - Use pydantic-settings or a thin manual layer

  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # E: API and CLI Surface
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: E01
    area: api-surface
    severity: medium
    title: "api.py still imports directly from scanner.py internals (_run_scan_payload)"
    detail: |
      src/prism/api.py imports:
        from prism.scanner import _run_scan_payload
        from prism.scanner import run_scan as _scanner_run_scan

      _run_scan_payload is a private function. api.py is the public surface
      and should not depend on private scanner internals.

    what_to_do:
      - Promote _run_scan_payload to a proper public seam in scanner_kernel
      - api.py imports from scanner_kernel, not scanner.py directly
      - Remove the scanner.py private function once API is pointed at the seam

  - id: E02
    area: api-surface
    severity: medium
    title: "No OpenAPI/REST API — programmatic consumers must use Python SDK"
    detail: |
      Prism has a Python API (api.py) and a CLI (cli.py), but no HTTP API.
      prism-learn and other consumers must either shell out to the CLI or
      import the Python package directly. This tightly couples consumers to
      the Python implementation.

    what_to_do:
      - Evaluate a lightweight FastAPI/Flask wrapper exposing scan_role, scan_collection, scan_repo
      - JSON request/response matching existing TypedDict contracts
      - OpenAPI spec auto-generated from the route definitions
      - CLI could optionally start a local API server for tooling integration

  - id: E03
    area: api-surface
    severity: low
    title: "CLI lacks streaming output / progress for large scans"
    detail: |
      The CLI produces no progress output during a scan. For large roles, users
      see nothing until the scan completes. This is poor UX and makes it hard
      to diagnose slow scans.

    what_to_do:
      - Implement a progress reporter using scan phase events (see C01)
      - CLI option: --progress / --no-progress
      - Stream phase names and timing to stderr (not stdout, to preserve JSON output)

  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # F: Testing and Quality
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: F01
    area: testing
    severity: high
    title: "src/ scanner_core has 10-30% coverage — it is live production code"
    detail: |
      The src/ lane is still production. src/prism/scanner_core/ modules have:
        - di.py: 17.6%
        - feature_detector.py: 6.8%
        - scan_runtime.py: 22.6%
        - variable_pipeline.py: 13.5%
        - variable_insights.py: 16.7%
        - scanner_context.py: 20.7%
        - scan_facade_helpers.py: 9.0%

      These are not untested edge cases — these are the core execution paths.

    what_to_do:
      - Either migrate fully to fsrc (then src/ coverage becomes irrelevant)
      - Or write unit tests for src/ scanner_core before next production use
      - Minimum target: 70% line coverage for production execution paths

  - id: F02
    area: testing
    severity: medium
    title: "No performance benchmarks for scan hot paths"
    detail: |
      There are no benchmarks measuring how long a full role scan takes, how
      YAML loading scales with file count, or what the marginal cost of
      additional task files is. This makes performance regressions invisible.

    what_to_do:
      - Add pytest-benchmark suite for: single task file parse, full small role scan, full large role scan
      - CI records benchmark results as artifacts (not as pass/fail initially)
      - Set budget thresholds once baseline is established

  - id: F03
    area: testing
    severity: low
    title: "No fuzz testing for YAML and Jinja parsers"
    detail: |
      Prism parses arbitrary user-controlled YAML and Jinja2 templates from
      Ansible roles. Malformed or adversarial inputs could cause crashes or
      unexpected behaviour. There is no fuzz test coverage.

    what_to_do:
      - Add hypothesis-based property tests for YAML parsing edge cases
      - Add hypothesis-based property tests for Jinja template scanning
      - Focus on: nested structures, unicode, very large files, circular refs

  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # G: Observability and Operations
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: G01
    area: observability
    severity: medium
    title: "Logging is ad-hoc — no structured scan telemetry"
    detail: |
      Logging uses standard Python logging with plain string messages in hot
      paths. There is no structured log schema, no scan-level telemetry (duration,
      file counts, cache hit/miss), and no hook for external observability tools.

    what_to_do:
      - Define a ScanTelemetry TypedDict: scan_duration_ms, files_read, cache_hits, plugin_key, errors
      - ScannerContext emits telemetry at completion into scan result metadata
      - Structured logging in JSON mode for CI/CD consumers
      - Optional metrics sink plugin slot in DI

  - id: G02
    area: observability
    severity: low
    title: "Error codes exist but error handling is inconsistent at boundaries"
    detail: |
      errors.py defines a good FailurePolicy and error code system, but:
        - Some paths raise raw ValueError/RuntimeError without error codes
        - scan_degraded flag is set but not consistently surfaced to API callers
        - No error aggregation — first failure terminates, others may be swallowed

    what_to_do:
      - Audit all raise statements in fsrc/ for raw exceptions (grep: raise ValueError, raise RuntimeError)
      - Wrap in PrismRuntimeError with an appropriate code where they cross module boundaries
      - Ensure scan_degraded + scan_errors is always present in API response on partial failure

  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  # H: Security
  # ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  - id: H01
    area: security
    severity: medium
    title: "No input path validation — role_path is trusted without sanitisation"
    detail: |
      role_path is accepted from API/CLI callers and used directly to construct
      filesystem paths for file reads. There is no validation that role_path is
      within expected bounds (e.g., no path traversal checks).

      For a library used programmatically, a caller could pass role_path="../../../etc"
      and Prism would happily read it.

    what_to_do:
      - Validate role_path is an absolute path and resolves within expected bounds
      - Add a path_safety_check utility at the API boundary
      - Document the trust model: "role_path is caller-trusted; sanitise before calling"

  - id: H02
    area: security
    severity: low
    title: "Jinja2 template rendering from role content is not sandboxed"
    detail: |
      Prism uses Jinja2 for rendering README output. If any role content is
      interpolated unsanitised into Jinja2 templates, server-side template injection
      is possible. Needs an audit to confirm scope.

    what_to_do:
      - Audit all Jinja2 Environment instantiations for autoescape and sandboxing config
      - Ensure role content is passed as data context, never as template source
      - Use jinja2.sandbox.SandboxedEnvironment for any path that evaluates role content

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SEQUENCING NOTES (to fill in when planning)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

sequencing_notes: |
  Suggested grouping for planning waves:

  Wave 0 — Prerequisite (unblocks everything):
    A01, A02 — dual-lane convergence. Until fsrc is the single lane,
    every other fix must land twice.

  Wave 1 — Plugin system hardening (independent of lane convergence):
    B01, B02, B04 — makes plugins reliable and discoverable
    D01 — config schema, needed before B01 entry_points work

  Wave 2 — Core extensibility (depends on Wave 0 + Wave 1):
    C01 — event system (unlocks C02, C03, E03)
    C02 — async I/O
    C03 — caching

  Wave 3 — API and surface polish:
    E01, E02, E03 — API/CLI improvements
    G01, G02 — observability

  Wave 4 — Quality and security:
    F01, F02, F03 — testing
    H01, H02 — security

  Deferred / optional:
    B03 — plugin sandboxing (expensive, low immediate risk)
    C04 — DI generics (low priority unless DI grows past 500 lines)
    D02 — env vars (nice to have)
    E02 — HTTP API (depends on consumer demand)

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# MIGRATION GAP FINDINGS (src/ → fsrc/ functional audit, 2026-04-21)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# These are functional gaps identified by comparing src/ (production) and
# fsrc/ (future lane) at the behaviour level, not just package names.
# Nothing has been fixed — this is a review-only finding list.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

migration_gaps:

  - id: MG-01
    severity: critical
    title: "CLI argument surface — 29 of 36 src options absent from fsrc"
    area: cli
    known_renames:
      - src: "--style-readme"
        fsrc: "--style-readme-path"
        note: "Renamed and moved to repo subcommand only in fsrc"
      - src: "--format json"
        fsrc: "--json"
        note: "format flag collapsed to a boolean --json flag; other formats (md/html/pdf) dropped"
    options_shared_unchanged:
      - "--repo-url"
      - "--repo-ref"
      - "--repo-role-path"
      - "--repo-style-readme-path"
      - "--repo-timeout"
    options_absent_from_fsrc:
      - "--compare-role-path"
      - "--style-source"
      - "--create-style-guide"
      - "--vars-context-path"
      - "--vars-seed"
      - "--concise-readme"
      - "--scanner-report-output"
      - "--include-scanner-report-link"
      - "--variable-sources"
      - "--readme-config"
      - "--adopt-heading-mode"
      - "--keep-unknown-style-sections"
      - "--policy-config"
      - "--fail-on-unconstrained-dynamic-includes"
      - "--fail-on-yaml-like-task-annotations"
      - "--ignore-unresolved-internal-underscore-references"
      - "--detailed-catalog"
      - "--task-parameters"
      - "--task-runbooks"
      - "--inline-task-runbooks"
      - "--runbook-output"
      - "--runbook-csv-output"
      - "--include-collection-checks"
      - "--feedback-from-learn"
      - "--output"
      - "--template"
      - "--dry-run"
      - "--verbose"
      - "--exclude-path"
    fsrc_equivalent: partial
    api_status: COMPLETE
    notes: >
      5 repo options are present unchanged. 2 options are renamed (--style-readme
      → --style-readme-path; --format json → --json). 29 options are entirely
      absent from the fsrc CLI parser.

      IMPORTANT: fsrc api.py scan_role() and scan_collection() already accept
      the full parameter set: detailed_catalog, concise_readme, runbook_output_dir,
      runbook_csv_output_dir, style_readme_path, policy_config_path, compare_role_path,
      vars_seed_paths, exclude_path_patterns, adopt_heading_mode, etc.
      The gap is purely in fsrc/src/prism/cli.py (parser + command dispatch)
      not wiring those parameters through to the API calls. No new API work needed.

  - id: MG-02
    severity: critical
    title: "scanner_config package entirely absent in fsrc"
    area: configuration
    what_is_missing: >
      src/prism/scanner_config/ (policy.py, patterns.py, readme.py,
      style.py, marker.py, section.py, legacy_retirement.py) handles:
        - Loading .prism.yml policy toggles from disk
        - 5-tier pattern override stack (built-in + system + XDG +
          repo-local + env-var PRISM_PATTERNS_PATH)
        - Remote community pattern fetch (fetch_remote_policy)
        - Style guide XDG/env/cwd/system/bundled precedence resolution
        - README section config and section visibility loading
        - Custom comment-doc marker prefix loading
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      fsrc scanners always run with hardcoded defaults. Users cannot
      override sensitivity, section aliases, variable guidance keywords,
      ignored identifiers, or style guide source via external config files.
      --policy-config is accepted by the API signature but silently ignored.

  - id: MG-03
    severity: high
    title: "feedback.py (prism-learn integration) absent in fsrc"
    area: feedback-integration
    what_is_missing: >
      src/prism/feedback.py defines FeedbackPayload, FeedbackRecommendation,
      FeedbackDefectCategory TypedDicts. load_feedback() loads a feedback
      JSON document from a local file or HTTP/HTTPS API endpoint (a
      prism-learn server). apply_feedback_recommendations() applies
      recommendations to scanner behaviour — currently driving override of
      include_collection_checks. Enables the prism-learn feedback loop.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      --feedback-from-learn CLI option does not exist in fsrc CLI.
      fsrc cli_app modules do not reference feedback at all.

  - id: MG-04
    severity: high
    title: "scan_for_default_filters / scan_for_all_filters public APIs absent"
    area: api-surface
    what_is_missing: >
      src exposes scan_for_default_filters(role_path, exclude_paths) and
      scan_for_all_filters(role_path, exclude_paths) as standalone public
      API functions. They walk task files and return per-occurrence dicts
      (file, line_no, line, match, args, filter_name) for Jinja filter
      usage auditing without requiring a full scan.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      The underlying _filter_scanner module exists in scanner_extract in
      both lanes but is not exposed at prism.api or any public surface
      in fsrc.

  - id: MG-05
    severity: high
    title: "resolve_default_style_guide_source absent in fsrc"
    area: configuration
    what_is_missing: >
      Implements XDG/env/cwd/system/bundled precedence resolution for
      STYLE_GUIDE_SOURCE.md: $PRISM_STYLE_SOURCE → ./STYLE_GUIDE_SOURCE.md
      → $XDG_DATA_HOME/prism/ → /var/lib/prism/ → bundled template.
      Used by both CLI and API when --create-style-guide is requested.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      style_guide_skeleton=True flows through fsrc API parameters but
      there is no XDG-aware path resolution to find the source file.

  - id: MG-06
    severity: high
    title: "collect_role_contents / build_comparison_report public APIs absent"
    area: api-surface
    what_is_missing: >
      collect_role_contents(role_path, exclude_paths) returns a dict of
      files in common role subdirectories (tasks, handlers, vars, defaults,
      templates, files, meta, molecule). build_comparison_report(target,
      baseline, exclude_paths) computes quality metrics for two roles and
      returns a comparison dict. Standalone public analysis utilities.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      scan_facade_helpers.py exists only in src/prism/scanner_core/.
      fsrc has no equivalent public comparison API.

  - id: MG-07
    severity: high
    title: "ignored_identifiers drastically reduced in fsrc (7 vs 70+ entries)"
    area: scan-quality
    what_is_missing: >
      src/prism/data/ignored_identifiers.yml contains 70+ Jinja2/Ansible
      built-in identifiers suppressed during variable reference discovery:
      Jinja builtins (callable, cycler, defined, float, joiner, keys,
      lipsum, lower, range, sequence, string, upper, values), Ansible
      keywords (apt, dnf, git, iptables, names, pip, rpm, yum),
      YAML/flow-control tokens (false, no, null, true, yes, absent,
      always, changed, description, failed, loop_var, msg, name, never,
      not, now, present, query, rc, required, results, skipped, stderr,
      stdout, undef, undefined, warnings), and more.
    fsrc_equivalent: partial
    fsrc_location: "fsrc/src/prism/scanner_plugins/ansible/variable_discovery.py IGNORED_IDENTIFIERS"
    notes: >
      fsrc IGNORED_IDENTIFIERS has only 7 entries: ansible_facts, groups,
      hostvars, inventory_hostname, item, omit, vars. The fsrc lane will
      produce dramatically more spurious undocumented-variable false-positives.
      Identifiers like name, when, results, stdout, stderr, rc, msg,
      changed, failed, skipped, defined will all appear as unresolved
      variable references in fsrc scans.

  - id: MG-08
    severity: high
    title: "Pattern policy override stack / remote fetch absent in fsrc"
    area: configuration
    what_is_missing: >
      src/prism/scanner_config/patterns.py implements a 5-tier policy
      stack: built-in YAML data files + /var/lib/prism/.prism_patterns.yml
      + $XDG_DATA_HOME/prism/.prism_patterns.yml + <repo>/.prism_patterns.yml
      + $PRISM_PATTERNS_PATH. fetch_remote_policy(url) downloads the
      community pattern repository. write_unknown_headings_log() logs
      unmatched section headings. sensitivity, section_aliases,
      variable_guidance_keywords, and ignored_identifiers are all
      configurable via this stack.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      --policy-config is accepted by fsrc API signatures but not connected
      to any loader. Custom org-wide sensitivity patterns, credential
      prefixes, section aliases, and variable guidance are silently ignored.

  - id: MG-09
    severity: high
    title: "Feedback integration missing from CLI command handlers"
    area: cli
    what_is_missing: >
      src handle_collection_command and handle_role_command both call
      resolve_include_collection_checks(args.feedback_from_learn,
      args.include_collection_checks) which loads prism-learn feedback
      and overrides the include_collection_checks flag based on aggregate
      scan intelligence.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      Compounds MG-03 (missing feedback module) and MG-01 (missing CLI
      args). Even if feedback were available, fsrc command handlers
      would not call it.

  - id: MG-10
    severity: medium
    title: "cli_app shared/presenters/runtime helpers absent in fsrc"
    area: cli
    what_is_missing: >
      cli_app/shared.py: resolve_effective_readme_config(),
      resolve_vars_context_paths(), save_style_comparison_artifacts().
      cli_app/presenters.py: REDACTION_PATTERNS (credential sanitization),
      YAML multiline block dumper, content truncation with markers.
      cli_app/runtime.py: persist_collection_role_markdown_documents()
      (writes roles/<name>.md beside collection output),
      finalize_repo_json_output().
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      Absence of persist_collection_role_markdown_documents means running
      prism collection in fsrc will not write individual role markdown
      files under roles/ directory. REDACTION_PATTERNS absence means
      credential-like strings in style comparison captures are not sanitized.

  - id: MG-11
    severity: medium
    title: "scan_role payload field alias normalization absent in fsrc"
    area: api-surface
    what_is_missing: >
      src api_layer/common.py normalize_scan_role_payload_shape() adds
      stable public field name aliases to the scan payload:
        variables       <- display_variables
        requirements    <- requirements_display
        default_filters <- undocumented_default_filters
      Consumers can always access stable public key names regardless of
      internal payload naming.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      fsrc api_layer/non_collection.py scan_role() returns raw run_scan()
      output without normalization. API consumers using
      payload["variables"] or payload["requirements"] will get KeyError
      on fsrc but succeed on src.

  - id: MG-12
    severity: low
    title: "__version__ attribute absent from fsrc package"
    area: packaging
    what_is_missing: >
      src/prism/init.py exposes __version__ = "0.1.0" at the package
      level for packaging and tests.
    fsrc_equivalent: not_found
    notes: >
      fsrc/src/prism/__init__.py exists with a docstring but no
      __version__ attribute. import prism; prism.__version__ raises
      AttributeError on fsrc.

  - id: MG-13
    severity: low
    title: "scanner_compat.render_compat import path absent in fsrc"
    area: compatibility
    what_is_missing: >
      src/prism/scanner_compat/render_compat.py re-exports internal
      scanner_readme functions at the prism.scanner_compat.render_compat
      import path for downstream consumers using the pre-refactor path.
    fsrc_equivalent: partial
    notes: >
      The underlying functions exist in fsrc scanner_readme but the
      compatibility import path prism.scanner_compat.render_compat
      does not exist. Narrow real-world exposure expected.

  - id: MG-14
    severity: critical
    title: "fsrc CLI has no __main__ entry point — all demos silently do nothing"
    area: demos
    root_cause: >
      fsrc/src/prism/cli.py has no 'if __name__ == "__main__": sys.exit(main())'
      block at the bottom. Running 'python -m prism.cli' imports the module and
      exits 0 without ever calling main(). argparse is never invoked, no scan
      runs, no files are written. Every invocation exits 0 silently.
    demo_failure_count: "8 of 8 scenarios produce zero output files against fsrc"
    confirmed_by: >
      Running 'python -m prism.cli role /tmp/nonexistent_role' against fsrc
      exits 0 with no output and no error. Running src exits non-zero (role not
      found). debug_readmes/option_demos/ directory is empty after a full fsrc
      demo run; src produces 6+ files in the same run.
    additional_issues: >
      Even after adding the __main__ entry point, 7 of 8 demo scenarios will
      still fail because the fsrc CLI parser lacks the args they use:
        - role-concise: --concise-readme (not in fsrc parser)
        - role-detailed-catalog: --detailed-catalog (not in fsrc parser)
        - role-styled: --style-readme (not in fsrc parser)
        - role-html: -f html (not in fsrc parser)
        - role-json: -f json (not in fsrc parser; --json is boolean only)
        - collection-md: -f md (not in fsrc parser)
        - collection-json: -f json (not in fsrc parser)
      Only role-default (role_path with no extra flags) would succeed after the
      __main__ fix alone.
    what_to_do: >
      Step 1 (immediate, unblocks 1/8): Add __main__ entry point to
      fsrc/src/prism/cli.py.
      Step 2 (depends on MG-01 CLI work, unblocks 7/8): Wire the 29 absent CLI
      options through the fsrc parser and command dispatch.
      Step 3: Validate demo parity between src and fsrc lanes.
    dependency: MG-01
